# Professional lab content

When writing or editing files in **cloudflare-security-lab** and similar public security repos:

## Framing

- Present work as **production-style edge security**, **lab automation**, and **real WAF engineering**
- Do **not** frame docs, README, or repo metadata as study material, job-prep, or hiring-context content
- Focus on attack patterns, rule design, validation with curl, and operational outcomes
- Write so reviewers see a practitioner portfolio and hands-on engineering work

## Preferred language

| Instead of job-prep tone | Use |
|--------------------------|-----|
| prep / study notes | operational notes |
| talking points for hiring | engineering note / engineering outcome |
| cheat sheet for Q&A | quick reference |
| narrative for recruiters | runbook / operational summary |

## Scope

Applies to: README, docs/, scripts/, commit messages, GitHub repo descriptions, and PR text for this project.

## Secrets and identifiers

- Never commit API tokens, `.env`, or `.cursor/mcp.json` with real credentials
- Do not hardcode zone ID, ruleset ID, or account IDs in committed files — use `.env` and placeholders in `.env.example`
- Lab domain names in curl examples are fine; resource IDs belong in local `.env` only
